<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="trna">tRNA</a> - Transfer <a href="#rna">RNA</a>. These special <a href="#rna">RNA</a>s have a particular structure and many chemical modifications. They are charged with <a href="#amino_acid">amino acids</a>; the charged tRNAs are then used in <a href="#protein">protein</a> synthesis i.e. <a href="#translation">translation</a>. The tRNA has a three <a href="#nucleotide">nucleotide</a> <a href="#antiCodon">anticodon</a> loop, which complements a three <a href="#nucleotide">nucleotide</a> <a href="#codon">codon</a> on an <a href="#mrna">mRNA</a> in the <a href="#ribosome">ribosome</a>, enabling the <a href="#ribosome">ribosome</a> to create a new peptide chain from the sequence of an <a href="#mrna">mRNA</a>.